  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Fernando Tatis Jr. Walks Off Atlanta in Ten Innings",
    "subheadline": "Dramatic Finish in the 10th Innings Lifts San Diego Padres",
    "lead_angle": "Fernando Tatis Jr. slapped a ground ball through the right side of a drawn-in infield, sending Petco Park into a frenzy and the San Diego Padres to a 7-6 walk-off victory over the Atlanta Braves. The 10th-inning single off Atlanta closer Raisel Iglesias scored the automatic runner from third, capping a tense, back-and-forth night. Iglesias was saddled with the loss after failing to record an out in the final frame. The win went to Mason Miller, who worked a scoreless top of the tenth to set up the finish.\n\nThe game was defined by a wild second inning that saw nine men cross the plate. Atlanta struck first, plating four runs highlighted by a solo shot from Mauricio Dubón and a two-run single by Rowdy Tellez. The lead was short-lived. San Diego answered immediately in the bottom half of the frame, storming back with five runs of its own. That counter-attack was punctuated by a towering two-run home run from Tatis that tied the game before the Padres scratched across one more to take the lead.\n\nTatis was the man of the hour for San Diego, finishing 2-for-5 with the decisive RBI and his earlier home run. He wasn't alone, as sparkplug Samad Taylor chipped in with a 3-for-4 night at the plate. For the Braves, Michael Harris II paced the offense with three hits in the losing effort. The victory keeps the Padres locked in a tight race for a postseason spot, providing a critical win against a fellow contender as the summer schedule heats up.",
    "reason": "Extra-inning walk-off — the purest combination of tension and resolution the sport offers."
  },
